<font color="#FF0000">GUN SHY, AND KILLER TEAMS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Dec 20 10:42:30 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Welcome home Dan Kadlec,<br>
I noticed that there was a Daniel Kadlec that served with the US Army in Vietnam, only one listed. <br>
Sorry for the filth on the site, there is a lot of help to be found here among those that served in an unpopular war. You're always welcome. Perhaps the story below will help you understand why sometimes we apprear gun shy.<br><br>
The Enemy in our midst<br>
In the middle of one of the fiercest fire fights in what we called Arizona Territory, in Quan Nam province South Vietnam, a North Vietnamese Soldier, in broken English kept yelling at us, as we laid pinned down alongside a bend in the river of finger lakes area.<br><br>
&quot;Cam-kook, cam-kook, Mahreene, mahreene, tonight you die, mahreene, mahreene tonight you die.&quot; <br><br>
The enemy was mocking us for having asked him for Identification, cam-kook, means identification in Vietnamese. It was a word we used often to try and identify who was traveling between the villages. He was in essence telling us, you dumb Marine you stopped me, questioned me and let me go. I fooled you with a false identification card. I was posing as something I’m not. Now I have you pinned down, we have you surrounded and tonight “Mahreene, tonight you die,’ <br><br>
Well, we didn’t die that day others came to our rescue and the hunter became the hunted. In Vietnam it would have been so easy to just open up, clear the area and move on, but we were there to do a job, for America and for the Vietnamese people. <br><br>
Often we suspected the person to be carrying a false identification card or papers, but we were limited as to what we could do. All too often we gave them the benefit of the doubt and allowed them to go through and pose among the genuine people of the local village. Often when we met a villager out in the boonies or near a rice paddy field we didn’t know if we were suppose to open fire, say hello, or reach out our hands and treat him as a fellow comrade.<br><br>
Killer Teams<br>
When we received incoming from our back we then knew we had just allowed an enemy in among us.<br>
The problem then was to go back and destroy the village or surgically remove the enemy from among the friendlies. To combat this threat at night we would send out killer teams, Marines, grunts, hard corps, gung ho Marines to go out and find the enemy. Those were the scariest ventures I ever went on, sometimes we were successful, often we found nothing but empty casings where the enemy had been.<br><br>
Those that post here anon, or under a false names who shoot at us in the back after we have reached out to a family member of a fallen comrade or a true veteran remind me of those communist trained NVA soldiers, who mocked us for allowing them to live or move in among the people. For allowing compassion, honor, trust and all that America stands for to help us make those decisions. We had asked them to identify themselves, so that we could respond appropriately, but they deceived us, but in the end it was the Vietnamese people that suffered the most, they lost their country, we lost many honorable men and our country lost its glory. <br><br>
The mockers here also remind me of the hatred the protestors and the anti-war demonstrators slung at us when we returned home. It reminds me of the pain we endured for having done only what our country asked us to do. <br><br>
I guess we will always have deceivers, mockers, traitors and cowards among our midst but they should not be the reason why, we as American fighting men, who have done our duty with honor and respect should doubt those that are honest in their heart in finding rest from the pain of that war.<br>
 I am, Cook Barela and those are my thoughts.<br><br>

